# cPanel File Manager


## How to Open File manager tool in Cpanel

- Log on to your cPanel account
- Under Files click on File Manager

```diagram

```

- In the pop up select Web root ( public_html) option, select options Show hidden Files and click on GO.

```diagram

```

- It should populate a new screen in which you can see the file manager with all the tools.

```diagram

```


## Creating New Folder


- Open the directory you want to create New Folder into by clicking on the name of the  folder name in the left side menu and then click on New Folder.

```diagram

```

- It will popup a new window. Then write your Folder name and then click on Create New Folder button

```diagram

```

- The new folder will appear in the chosen location.

## Creating New File

- Open the directory you want to create New File into by clicking on the name of the  folder name in the left side menu and then click on New File

```diagram

```

- It will popup a new window. Write your file name  and then click on Create New File

```diagram

```

- The new folder will appear in the chosen location and you are done.

## Uploading New Files

- Open the directory you want to upload data into by clicking on the name of the  folder name in the left side menu and then click on Upload button

```diagram

```

- On the next screen click on Choose File button, which will show you pop up of your local computer from which you need to upload your files.

```diagram

```

- Now click on Choose find the file you want to upload from the popup on your local computer

```diagram

```

- Select the file that you want to upload Then Click on OK or Open

```diagram

```

- Wait until the file gets uploaded and you are done. 

## Change the Permission of File/Folder

- Select File/Folders from the from File Manger you want to change permission

```diagram

```

- Then click on Change Permission Button or click the current permission under Perms Tab


```diagram

```

- Select the permission to want to set and then click Change Permissions

## How to Edit A File from cPanel

- Open cPanel file manager and go to the file location.
- Select the file you want to edit  from file manager 

```diagram

```

- Click on the Edit link in the top menu of your window. This will open a new window with the content of the file displayed. You can use more sophisticated editors as the Code Editor and the HTML Editor

```diagram

```

- Click on the Save Changes button when you are ready. The file is saved and the changes will take effect from now on.

## How can I Extract/Compress a File

**Extracting**

- Open cPanel file manager and go to the archive file location
- Select the archive file you want to extract

```diagram

```

- Then click on the Extract button in the top menu of your window.

```diagram

```

- Select the location where you want to extract the archive file and then click on Extract File button

```diagram

```

**Compressing**

- You can also create your own archives. 
- Select the files and folders which you want to include in the archive.

```diagram

```

- Click Compress in the top menu

```diagram

```

- From the new popup window select the archive type and write save location and then click Compress File

```diagram

```

## What is .htaccess and How can I Edit it via cPanel

The htaccess file is a configuration file which is used on Apache based web servers to control many features of the server.

The file itself is just a small basic text file and can be edited via your cPanel file manager or you can download the file, edit it and reupload it.

Using .htaccess you can redirect pages, change the extensions of pages, password protect directories and much much more. 

The default location of .htaccess file is /home/username/public_html

- Login to cPanel of your account and then open Filemanager
- Select the .htaccess and click on Edit from the top menu list.

```diagram

```

- It will open a new window with the content of your .htaccess file

```diagram

```

- Once your modifications are completed, then click on Save Changes Button

```diagram

```
